					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Nintendulator emulates things on a lower level.  It may check for pending NMI every CPU cycle because the NES does -- however it will not actually make the NMI happen until the CPU is between instructions -- so the only cycle where a pending NMI really matters is the 2nd-to-last cycle of an instruction.</div>
<br />
<br />- What a coincidence. RockNES does that too... ^_^;; Hehehe
<br />- I will explain it a bit:
<br />
<br />1. verify the flags (nmi_trigger = cpu_nmi_request).
<br />2. fetch a byte
<br />- 2a: ppu runs for 3 cycles
<br />- 2b: byte is read
<br />3. Instruction is executed.
<br />
<br />- OK, if a NMI occurs during 2a (cpu_nmi_request = 1), it will not be triggered after that instruction. The nmi_trigger flag is verified right when an instruction is finished; if <em>true</em>, then a NMI is triggered.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><strong>Zepper</strong><br /><a href="http://rocknes.web.fc2.com/" class="postlink"><em>RockNES developer</em></a></div>
